LIMIT in SQL

The LIMIT clause is used to restrict the number of rows returned by a query.

👉 It is mainly used for:

Pagination
Fetching top records
Performance optimization
Basic Syntax
SELECT * FROM table_name
LIMIT n;

👉 n = number of rows to display

Example 1: Get first 5 employees
SELECT * FROM Employee
LIMIT 5;
Example 2: Top 3 highest salaries
SELECT * FROM Employee
ORDER BY salary DESC
LIMIT 3;

👉 First sort, then limit

Example 3: Pagination (Very Important)
Page 1 (First 5 records)
SELECT * FROM Employee
LIMIT 5 OFFSET 0;
Page 2 (Next 5 records)
SELECT * FROM Employee
LIMIT 5 OFFSET 5;

👉 Formula:

OFFSET = (page - 1) * limit
Real-Time Example
E-commerce Product Listing
SELECT * FROM Products
ORDER BY price DESC
LIMIT 10;

👉 Shows top 10 expensive products

